<br>
First off, RK2 is more difficult. It has the attraction of being less crowded, and generally more friendly. But on the other hand it is harder to find buffs, teammates, and all the other stuff that makes this an MMORPG rather than just a single player RPG.<br>
<br>
Most of all, I cannot help you on RK1. By this I mean direct physical help as in equipment, credits, and escorts to places, etc.<br>
<br>
First off, the best site for general info today is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.anarchyarcanum.com">www.anarchyarcanum.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
Starting your first character off, with no creds and no idea how the game works is HARD. On the other hand, you have picked the easiest class to do so with. The MA is a good, solid choice, with any race, at any level, on any dimension!<br>
<br>
If you want to start a character on RK1, look me up as Hildegaard, a L172 Omni Doctor. Try this -<br>
<br>
/tell Hildegaard Hello, this is yournamehere, from TPB!<br>
<br>
Catch me online, identify yourself as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  being from TPB</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and I'll help you out with some creds, equip, advice, etc. If I seem to ignore your first message, just send it again, or even a third time if need be. I'm probably just AFK, or missed your message in the battle-spam. Stuff on the console can fly by in a BIG hurry!<br>
<br>
For starts with mechanics, try the built-in help system. Type -<br>
<br>
/help<br>
<br>
Like that, and the system will reply with a list of specific subjects. then type -<br>
<br>
/help missions<br>
<br>
- or whatever the subject of your query is. This will get you most of the info you need on the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  basic</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mechanics of the game.<br>
<br>
Familiarize yourself with the GUI for starts. Look at the icons at the top right of the screen. You can click on them to open and close, or you can use (Ctrl-1) through (Ctrl-9).<br>
<br>
Next up, there are TWO maps available to you. the local map you toggle on and off with (Ctrl-6), and that one is precious for guiding you around cities.<br>
<br>
The other you toggle on and off with the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  P</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> key. This is a so-called &quot;Planet Map&quot;, and the stock one is about as useful as tits on a boar <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
When you're a bit more settled-in with the real basics, try Dovve's map upgrade, from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://peacefairchild.tripod.com">peacefairchild.tripod.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Dovve is a design architect by trade, and her graphic work is just exquisite. Installing this does, however, require making a directory, copying files, and that sort of real basic computer knowledge. On the up side, Dovve's map is not just sweet-looking, it is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  hellaciously</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> useful, in that the zoomed-out view shows you the whole wompa network.<br>
<br>
AO is a wonderfully, delightfully, infuriatingly complex game. It will make you laugh, it will make you cry, it will make you howl in victory, and it will at times make you want to put your fist right through the monitor <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Although I did not beta, I've played AO since the 3rd day of US retail launch. That was over a year ago, and I am still learning stuff. Don't expect to master it in a week!<br>
<br>
