<br>
I agree with Alecto on Tir and Omni 1/Ent......both are extremely confusing to get around in, especially for someone just starting out. Lag is also a huge issue in both zones. I'm not sure of the Omni mirror city to Athen...It may be Rome. Pubilus can direct you there. Old Athen and W Athen is the best place to put down roots if you are Clan though. Make sure you scan somewhere in Old Athen (even though technically you don't need to scan until lvl 20), as if you die you will be rezzed in Old Athen instead of the ent park where you first started. A nightmare, if you you are a noob to the world.<br>
<br>
A few other tips:<br>
1) Go ahead and grab your lvl 10 (or 20 if you can squeeze into them) implants...They are in your basic shops already assembled. They are not optimal, but they help in the lower lvls until you learn how to get your custom set built (that, my friend is another tutorial altogether).<br>
<br>
2) If you are going to use a weapon (ie. the claw, the only one worth a damn at lower lvls) go ahead and start using it now so that you can keep up with your skills early on. IPs are a major issue early on, so if you decide to start using a weapon at a later lvl it will be difficult to play &quot;catch up&quot; in the skills required.<br>
<br>
3) Bio met, Sense Imp, Psy Mod, Time&amp;Space and treatment are your main nano and aiding skills that you need to keep raised. First Aid is important, but not as much so as those other 5 skills. You might want to raise Mat met to 108 in order use Muscle Stim....with the general +12 str buff, you can bump your str +24. This will help with equiping armor and some MA skill increase. After that, never touch Mat met again.) Mat creation is a controversial skill for most MAs...it allows you run your AC buffs. Most old school MAs will tell you not to worry about it, since it doesn't really raise your AC that much and it costs alot of IPs to raise. Personally I think that in the lower lvls it helps alot. I raised mine enough to use Greater Wooden Skin, and have not touched it since. It'a an individual preference thing though.<br>
<br>
4) Computer Literacy, although a blue skill (green, aqua, blue, and dark blue are the skill colors...green costs the least amount of IPs to raise while dark blue costs the most), is never the less a very important skill for MAs, esp if you solo. The more NCUs you have (you start with eight) , the more buffs you can run. You have to equip NCU belts and NCU memory modules, both of which uses Comp Lit skill, in order to raise your NCU count. Comp Lit also lets you use the Grid (a place which takes you all over the world, some places not accessed by Whompas), plus allows you to get better prices at the shop terminals in the Supermarkets. I normally keep it maxed for the first 20 or 30 lvls, then taper off and raise it as needed (while using temp implants) to equip better belts and memory. Keep in mind, the higher your base intelligence, the better your comp lit, map nav, trade skills and nano skills will be.<br>
<br>
5) Map navigation needs to be gotten to 130 as quick as you can get it there. At 130 you an upgrade your map reader to see monsters on the map. By that time you should already have direction arrow, machine, and people upgrades...not to mention a slew of maps for different zones. You can use implants to get to 130, as maps and reader upgrades are a one time upload. Many will tell you to stop there since you can use Dove's map to travel pretty much anywhere in the world you want, but I think a healthy map system is pretty important (until you get a Yalmaha which is the only way to travel IMHO) as it allows you to see what's on the horizion enemy wise. If you are running on the ground keep raising map nav and upload as many zone maps as you can....a deep red can't kill you if you avoid it.<br>
<br>
There are many, many more tips out there that we, many who have been here since the beginning, have available to our younger inexperienced brethern. Never hesitate to ask us a question. You'll find most ppl on this board are very helpful and friendly, and will gladly chime in and help when they can.<br>
Welcome to Rubi-Ka!!<br>
